o track `lo` and `hi` relative to position, reducing the state space. A standard O(n * sum) DP where sum = total of all a_i would work but even that might be tight. However, the given code's approach of tracking all reachable positions with Pareto-optimal (lo, hi) pairs will explode in both time and memory.\n\n**Bug: lo and hi initialization:**\nThe starting state is `dp[0] = [(0, 0)]`. The first segment starts at 0 and extends to either +a[0] or -a[0]. The coverage includes [0, a[0]] or [-a[0], 0]. So lo should include 0 and hi should include 0 (the start). The code computes `nlo = min(lo, nx)` and `nhi = max(hi, nx)` where nx is the new endpoint. But the segment covers from x to nx (or nx to x). The coverage includes all points between x and nx, so hi should be `max(hi, x, nx)` and lo should be `min(lo, x, nx)`. Since x is between lo and hi already (as the current position was reached through previous segments), this is actually fine \u2014 x is already within [lo, hi]. So the lo/hi update is correct.\n\nThe main issue is **TLE** for large inputs.\n\n```json\n{\"verdict\": \"FAIL\", \"bugs\": [{\"description\": \"TLE: The number of distinct reachable positions can grow up to O(sum of a_i) = O(10^7), and iterating over all positions for each of n=10^4 segments leads to O(n * sum) = O(10^11) operations, far exceeding time limits.\", \"line\": 30, \"severity\": \"critical\", \"triggering_input\": \"1\\n10000\\n1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 1000 ... (10000 values of 1000)\"}]}\n```",
